00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:04.580
at  some of the recent trends in popular music.

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:08.280
And we might as well start with this 
term, "tropical house",

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:14.320
coined sort of as a joke in 2014 by 22 year old Australian DJ Thomas Jack.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:18.260
Tropical house is a somewhat slower tempo house music

00:01:18.260 --> 00:01:23.200
that often features pan flutes, marimbas, steel drums and other instruments

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:28.940
originating from the Caribbean or Africa to give the sound a more mellow tropical vibe.

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:35.760
Thanks to Thomas Jack, who by the way is now pretty much over tropical house, and other producers like Kygo,

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:42.000
this subgenre swept rapidly across the world and right into the heart of the commercialized mainstream

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.980
with mega hits like Felix Jaehn's remix of Omi's "Cheerleader".

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:54.300
And pretty much every hit of Justin Bieber's comeback tour.

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:02.800
I think there's little doubt that these songs are surfing the tropical house wave.

00:02:03.280 --> 00:02:07.580
But even these mega hits it could be argued owe their sound to Dancehall.

00:02:07.900 --> 00:02:12.540
In fact, you could probably say that about the whole genre. Bieber's 'Sorry', the instrumental beat

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:16.880
of which is playing under my narration right now, is a perfect example.

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:19.200
The Addictive drum pattern at the heart of this song

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:24.020
is called "dembow", which takes its name from the 1990 Shabba Ranks' song.

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:31.040
Shabba Ranks was probably the most popular Dancehall artist of the 90s

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:34.060
and one of the first to gain worldwide recognition.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:39.020
