For the uninitiated, Dancehall can trace its roots all the way back to the independence of Jamaica in 1962

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:18.260
after over three hundred years of British rule and the rise of Ska music.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:22.500
You can go even further back than that since ska is really just a combination of elements

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:27.980
already found in Jamaican Mento music and calypso music from Trinidad and Tobago

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:32.460
and both of these have their origins in 
West African tribal music.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:38.040
Ska takes these traditional rhythms and mixes them with the Jazz and Rhythm 'n Blues

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:40.440
that was popular in the United States at the time.

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:45.600
Its emphasis on the second and fourth beats in the bar gave the music a jumpy feel.

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:51.060
Great for dancing, which is one of the reasons it took off in Britain in the 1960s as well.

00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:57.260
But as the post-independence economic boom in 
Jamaica sagged under rising poverty and rising crime,

00:03:57.260 --> 00:04:02.100
Ska eventually slowed down and evolved into Reggae,

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:08.680
a politically-motivated genre of music that would 
culminate in the global popularity of Bob Marley.

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:10.680
