00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:24.480
By the time Marley died in 1981, reggae was a worldwide phenomenon.

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:30.640
But back in the cities of Jamaica, musicians began turning to more up-tempo sounds again.

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:37.120
See, one of the crucial development of Jamaican music was the release of what's called "B-side" versions,

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:42.020
which is basically the instrumental track of the song in question on the other side of the record.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:46.640
Jamaican DJs began singing and essentially rapping over these versions

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:51.820
and this is the precursor of American Hip-hop but it's also the origin of Dancehall.

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:58.120
Using new technologies, producers dubbed and distorted popular 'riddims' for DJs to perform over.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:04.980
The same riddim can be used in dozens of songs and that brings us back to 'Work'.

00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:11.000
The instrumental to this song, for example, comes from the popular "Sail Away" riddim,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.020
